headline.main: Mosquito Study May Give Clue to Human Obesity

byline.original: By DAVID BINDER Special to The New York Times

docs.abstract: Dr E Van Handel studies obesity in mosquitoes for clues in controlling human obesity; links endocrine glands
docs.lead_paragraph: VERO BEACH, Fla., Oct. 4 --The fact that female mosquitoes grow fatter than male mosquitoes has led a Dutch biologist here to speculate that further study of this phenomenon may lead to means for controlling obesity in humans.
docs.snippet: VERO BEACH, Fla., Oct. 4 --The fact that female mosquitoes grow fatter than male mosquitoes has led a Dutch biologist here to speculate that further study of this phenomenon may lead to means for controlling obesity in humans.

headline.main: RUTGERS APPOINTS DEAN OF MEDICINE; Dr. DeWitt Stetten to Head School Opening in '65

docs.abstract: Leaves Natl Health Insts to head Rutgers U Med School
docs.lead_paragraph: NEW BRUNSWICK, N.J., Oct. 6--Dr. DeWitt Stetten Jr., a medical director with the National Institutes of Health, will head the Rutgers University Medical School.
docs.snippet: NEW BRUNSWICK, N.J., Oct. 6--Dr. DeWitt Stetten Jr., a medical director with the National Institutes of Health, will head the Rutgers University Medical School.
